# Plan: Codex Skill Junction Layer

Track ID: 20260702-codex-skill-symlinks
Plan created: 2026-07-02
Stage: 1 - Plan Creation only

## Restated goal/outcome

Make `C:\Users\DaveWitkin\.codex\skills\` a thin Windows junction layer over the user's canonical OpenCode skill stores, keep it synchronized by a weekly OpenCode Scheduler job, and document the architecture and maintenance steps.

## Restated constraints/non-goals

- Stage 1 must not execute implementation; this plan is for later execution.
- Use PowerShell-first via the bash tool; every bash call must include explicit `timeout`.
- Do not use native Read/Edit/Write/glob/grep if they are returning `Bun is not defined`.
- Use `-LiteralPath`, double-quoted Windows paths, and avoid interactive or indefinite commands.
- Do not edit native skill content except for the Phase M migration of `nlm-skill` and `pptx-to-pdf-converter` out of native into real vault folders; otherwise only create/update junctions and external docs/scripts/job JSON.
- Exclude `.system` and `_archived_skills`.
- Do not rewrite the existing marketing `skill-sync-monitor.ps1`; only document it as related/stale.

## Restated definition of done

- Every included vault/native skill has a Codex junction pointing at the canonical source.
- Real duplicate Codex folders are backed up and converted, or recorded as explicit exceptions.
- A dry-run/apply reconciliation script exists at `C:\development\_shared-scripts\codex-skill-junction-reconcile.ps1` and writes reports.
- A weekly OpenCode Scheduler job exists in global scope and appears Ready under `\OpenCode\`.
- Runbook and stale-doc annotation exist.
- Backups and reconciliation reports are available for validation.

## Global executor preflight

Use PowerShell-first through the bash tool for every command. Every bash tool call must include an explicit timeout such as `120000`. Start each command with `$ErrorActionPreference = 'Stop'`. Do not run interactive commands.

---

